# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1883-philadelphia-quakers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1883 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 13th season of the franchise.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters won their third National League pennant, their third in six years.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] This is also generally recognized as the year during which the team's nickname became the **Boston Beaneaters**.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1883 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 52–45 record, good for fifth place in the National League.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-buffalo-bisons-season] Star slugger Dan Brouthers won his second consecutive NL batting title with a .374 average and Pud Galvin posted 46 wins.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1883 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 12th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the eighth in the National League and the sixth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished second in the National League with a record of 59–39.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-cleveland-blues-season] The **1883 Cleveland Blues** finished the season at 55–42, fourth place in the National League.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-columbus-buckeyes-season] The **1883 Columbus Buckeyes** finished with a 32–65 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-columbus-buckeyes-season] This was the first season in the major leagues for the team.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The 1883 season was the first in the history of the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team was founded earlier in the year as a replacement for the Worcester franchise.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] It was the first year Philadelphia was represented in the National League since the original Athletics were disbanded in 1876 after refusing to finish the season.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The American Association's Philadelphia Athletics had been founded a year earlier.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team opened the year managed by Bob Ferguson; however, he was fired as manager after a disappointing 4–13 start and replaced by Blondie Purcell.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team finished the season 17–81, worst in the National League.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies played their first game ever on April 2, 1883, and defeated the amateur Manayunk Ashlands in an exhibition game by the score of 11–0 at Recreation Park.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies hosted Providence at Recreation Park in their first regular season game on May 1, 1883.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] One thousand fans saw John Coleman start the game for the Phillies and relinquish the first hit in the first inning to Providence first baseman Joe Start.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies scored first and took a three to zero lead into the eighth inning when Providence scored four times to win the game.
[src:1883-philadelphia-quakers-season/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies would lose their first eleven games, and not win their first game at home in Philadelphia until June 6, 1883.
